The problem you have:

1- You want to read a file line by line.

2- You want to create a student object for the data you obtained from each line.

3- You want to add the created object to the array list.

The solution&#39;s algorithm for each step respectively:

1- You can read a line as a string, and iterate it for each line using a loop until there is no other line.

2- You can parse the string you obtained in 1-st step. You can use .split(String delimiter) method of String class. This makes you able to split a string to an array of strings. It cuts the string from the indexes that there is a delimiter. For example, if you have the String &quot;Hi,How,Are,You&quot; and the Delimiter: &quot;,&quot; then your new String array will be: {&quot;Hi&quot;,&quot;How&quot;,&quot;Are&quot;,&quot;You&quot;}.

Then you should think about how you convert a string formatted integer to an integer. e.g. &quot;123&quot; to 123. For that aim, you can use Integer.parseInt(String stringFormattedInteger).

3- You should use .add(Object o) method of ArrayList Template Class.

I suppose that you have a class **Student** with only *id* and *name* properties and a constructor taking *id* and *name* respectively.I also suppose you have such a format in the txt file:

(Student ID) (Student Name)

For Example:

1 Samantha Black

2 James Wizard


Then your code should be similar to this:

    try{
    	File file = new File(&quot;File.txt&quot;)
    	FileReader fr=new FileReader(file);
    	BufferedReader br=new BufferedReader(fr);
    	ArrayList&lt;Student&gt; students = new ArrayList&lt;Student&gt;();
    	String line;
    	while((line=br.readLine())!=null)  
    	{  
    		int id = Integer.parseInt(line.split(&quot; &quot;)[0]);
    		String name = line.split(&quot; &quot;)[1];
    		Student s = new Student(id, name);
    		students.add(s);
    
    	}  
    }catch(IOException e){
