`myObject2` is an instance of a proxy class, generated at runtime by Hibernate using [Byte Buddy][1]. The generated proxy intercepts all method invocations, that&#39;s why `getClass()` returns different results.

As an alternative to `getClass()`, using `instanceof` might be another approach:
```
if ( !(this instanceof MyClass &amp;&amp; o instanceof MyClass) )
{
   return false;
}
```

However keep in mind that `instanceof` has its [drawbacks][2]. It violates the symmetry principle. 

You shouldn&#39;t compare these objects in the first place, since a new object should be different from a Hibernate managed one that has a persistent state.


  [1]: https://bytebuddy.net/#/
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/596462/any-reason-to-prefer-getclass-over-instanceof-when-generating-equals

